<module>
    <h>Màiri</h>
    <p><g>Màiri</g>
        <en>Mary</en> is a feminine <a href="?xx=nouns/anthroponymic_proper_nouns">anthroponymic
            proper noun</a>.</p>

    <section id="forms">
        <h>forms</h>
        <p>The principal parts of <g>Màiri</g> are – <ul>
                <li><m>Màiri</m> – nominative/dative/genitive (singular)</li>
                <li><m>A Mhàiri!</m> – vocative</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>dependents</h>
        <section id="deps-bare">
            <h>bare</h>
            <p>Like other (proper) nouns, <g>Màiri</g> can occur on its own, without any
                dependents.</p>
            <p>Some examples – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Bha falt bàn air <m>Màiri</m>.</gd>
                        <tr>Mary had fair hair.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 9 [adapted]</ref>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <gd>A bheil <m>Màiri</m> sgìth an diugh?</gd>
                        <tr>Is Mary tired today?</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 9 [adapted]</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section id="deps-mods">
            <h>modifiers</h>
            <p>Like other (proper) nouns, <g>Màiri</g> can be (post-)modified by an (attributive) <a
                    href="?xx=adjectives/adjective">adjective</a>.</p>
            <p>Some examples – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Tha <m>Màiri bheag</m> sgìth.</gd>
                        <tr>Little Mary is tired.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 9</ref>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Cha robh <m>Màiri bhàn</m> anns an achadh an diugh.</gd>
                        <tr>Fair-headed Mary was not in the field today.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 9 [adapted]</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section id="uses-sbj">
            <h>subject</h>
            <p>Like other (proper) nouns, <g>Màiri</g> can be used as the subject of a <a
                    href="?xx=verbs/verbs">verb</a>.</p>
            <p>Examples with the predicative verb <a href="?gd=bi"><g>bi</g></a>
                <en>be</en> – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Nach robh <m>Màiri</m> ag obair?</gd>
                        <tr>Wasn’t Mary working?</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 6 [adapted]</ref>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Tha <m>Màiri</m> beag bàn.</gd>
                        <tr>Mary is small and fair-haired.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 8</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
            <p>Examples with <a href="?xx=nouns/demonstrative_pronouns">demonstrative pronouns</a> used as copular verbs – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Seo <m>Màiri</m>.</gd>
                        <tr>This is Mary.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 15</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
            <p><g>Màiri</g> can also be used as part of a conjoined subject linked by <a
                    href="?gd=agus"><g>agus</g></a>
                <en>and</en> – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Bha <m>Màiri agus Calum</m> ag obair anns an achadh.</gd>
                        <tr>Mary and Malcolm were working in the field.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 6–7</ref>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Nach eil <m>Seònaid agus Màiri</m> anns an sgoil an diugh?</gd>
                        <tr>Aren’t Janet and Mary in the school today?</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 15 [228] [adapted]</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
